\section{Regulatory conventions}{

ICH E3 and common pharma submission standards specify:

\strong{Labelling:}
\itemize{
\item Footnote labels use lower-case letters in square brackets: \verb{[a]}, \verb{[b]},
\verb{[c]}. Do \strong{not} use numeric labels — \verb{[1]}, \verb{[2]} are reserved for
literature references.
\item Do \strong{not} begin the footnote section with the word "Note" or "Notes:".
}

\strong{Layout:}
\itemize{
\item Each footnote on its own line, left-aligned, same or smaller font than
the table body.
\item RTF/SAS submissions: limit to \strong{8 footnotes} per table for full
compatibility with standard TLG macro footnote slots.
}

\strong{Ordering:}
\itemize{
\item \verb{[a]}, \verb{[b]}, … content footnotes first (in the order symbols appear
reading left-to-right, top-to-bottom through the table).
\item Abbreviation expansion line last (e.g. \code{"AE = Adverse Event; FAS = Full Analysis Set; SD = Standard Deviation."}).
\item Source / data-cut note on the \strong{final page only}
(\code{placement = "last"}).
}

\strong{Common regulatory footnote patterns:}
\itemize{
\item \emph{Percentage denominator}: \code{"[a] Percentages are based on N in the column header."} — required whenever \verb{n (\%)} columns appear.
\item \emph{MedDRA coding}: \code{"[a] Coded using MedDRA Version XX.X."} — for AE,
medical history, and prior/concomitant medication tables.
\item \emph{Subject counting}: \code{"[a] A subject is counted only once for multiple events within the same System Organ Class or Preferred Term."} — AE
tables where events > subjects is possible.
\item \emph{Dagger symbol}: use \code{{fr_dagger()}} and \code{{fr_ddagger()}} markup for
treatment-related or serious AE markers.
}
